    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_28898417" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28898417" />
    <a title="Huan-hua" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1332976-huan-hua"><img alt="Huan-hua" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28898417?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Huan-hua" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Huan-hua" href="/user/show/1332976-huan-hua">Huan-hua</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">lovers of post-apocalyptic fiction</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Huan-hua by: </span>
      book club
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer28898417&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28898417" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12595415147075920102">I loved this book. Someone else picked it for my book club a few years ago, and most of the people in the group hated it, so it&apos;s not for everyone--but I really enjoyed it. <br/><br/>I&apos;m a sucker for postapocalyptic sci-fi, and this is subtler and gentler than the usual overblown, testosterone-laden books about hordes of zombies and cannibals and crazy-eyed survivalists with guns... it does a nice job of conveying the image of the world ending not with a bang, but a whimper. Most of humanity has been wipe</span>
  <span id="freeText12595415147075920102" style="display:none">I loved this book. Someone else picked it for my book club a few years ago, and most of the people in the group hated it, so it's not for everyone--but I really enjoyed it. <br /><br />I'm a sucker for postapocalyptic sci-fi, and this is subtler and gentler than the usual overblown, testosterone-laden books about hordes of zombies and cannibals and crazy-eyed survivalists with guns... it does a nice job of conveying the image of the world ending not with a bang, but a whimper. Most of humanity has been wiped out, and it's not necessarily every remaining person's first impulse to kill everyone else they meet.<br /><br />As a bonus, it's set in my hometown, Berkeley, so it gave me a bit of a thrill to read about Ish wandering the empty streets of the Berkeley hills, looking for his parents' house, or standing in the middle of the Bay Bridge, looking out on the Bay and the silent, still freeways; and later on, constructing bows and arrows among the rolling golden hills and live oaks of the familiar Northern California landscape.<br /><br />One of the other reviewers said they thought this book was too dated and it was hard to get past the descriptions of things like turning on the radio and waiting for the tubes to heat up, but I thought the book had actually aged really well. I didn't realize until I got about halfway through that it had been written decades back. <br /><br />The one part that really struck me as unpleasantly dated was Ish's visit to a black family's farm, when he thinks to himself how easy it would be for him to move in and lord it over them, because it had been the natural order for so long that they would just accept his domination and allow him to live like a king off their labors. The book, and Ish's thinking, are products of the time and place, I guess.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12595415147075920102" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

